      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Hananiah the ruler of the palace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Hananiah the governor of the castle.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " On the castle or ‘Bira’ see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The ‘governor of the castle’ would be an official of great importance, being probably in command of troops for the purpose of keeping order in the city. ‘He’ refers to Hananiah. Possibly Nehemiah’s appointment of two officers to the command of the city corresponds with the mention of the two men in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", who were ‘rulers of half the district of Jerusalem.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a faithful man, and feared God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 18:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ‘able men, such as fear God, men of truth, hating unjust gain.’ The Hebrew is noticeable; not absolutely ‘a man of truth,’ but ‘such as only a man of truth is.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "above many",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. more than most. LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "παρὰ πολλούς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Vulg. ‘plus cæteris.’ The phrase which only occurs here in the O.T. has a very lifelike ring.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Hanani and Hananiah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This appointment of two municipal officers to have charge of Jerusalem recalls the mention of two \"rulers\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 3:9, 12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", each of whom had authority-over half the district dependent on Jerusalem, and amounts to an \"undesigned coincidence.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The ruler of the palace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Rather, \"the commandant of the fort,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the officer in charge of the temple fortress (see above, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Nehemiah 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The watching of the city provided for. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 7:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " When the wall was built, Nehemiah set up the doors in the gates, to complete the fortification of Jerusalem (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Then were the gatekeepers, the singers, and the Levites entrusted with the care (הפּקד, praefici; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 12:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The care of watching the walls and gates is meant in this connection. According to ancient appointment, it was the duty of the doorkeepers to keep watch over the house of God, and to open and close the gates of the temple courts; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 9:17-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 26:12-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The singers and the Levites appointed to assist the priests, on the contrary, had, in ordinary times, nothing to do with the service of watching. Under the present extraordinary circumstances, however, Nehemiah committed also to these two organized corporations the task of keeping watch over the walls and gates of the city, and placed them under the command of his brother Hanani, and of Hananiah the ruler of the citadel. This is expressed by the words, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 7:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : I gave Hanani ... and Hananiah ... charge over Jerusalem. הבּירה is the fortress or citadel of the city lying to the north of the temple (see rem. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Nehemiah 2:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in which was probably located the royal garrison, the commander of which was in the service of the Persian king. The choice of this man for so important a charge is explained by the additional clause: \"for he was a faithful man, and feared God above many.\" The כּ before אישׁ is the so-called Caph veritatis, which expresses a comparison with the idea of the matter: like a man whom one may truly call faithful. מרבּים is comparative: more God-fearing than many.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]